The Action Democratic Party (ADP), has appealed to  the Federal government led by President Muhammadu Buhari, not to neglect the private sector in giving palliative packages meant to cushion effects of the lock down to contain the spread of Coronavirus.  The party while reacting to the live broadcast made by the President on Monday evening  on the need to extend the lockdown for another 14 days noted that the private sector should be considered since it has the larger number of employees.  The National Publicity Secretary of the party, Prince Adelaja Adeoye noted that, “We must prepare not only to contain the Corona Virus, but also consider the effect of the lockdown on the employers of Labour and their employees, who carries the largest workforce.  “Some of them might resort into downsizing after the pandemic is over, because of how bad they might have been affected. To avoid massive job cut, the government at both Federal and State level should work out some relief for these employers, in form of supports, “ADP noted.  The party stressed further that, “These employees, have their tax records with the government, arguing that this is the time they needed government supports the most, as there is a projection that, economy might be  plundered, which will affect many of them, especially the entrepreneurs and small scale businesses.  “While it is appreciated that President Buhari has increased the social benefits from 2.6 million households to 3.6 million, which shows an addition of one million households, there must be transparency and accountability in the process of making these funds available to the beneficiaries, so that the real vulnerable Nigerians will benefit and their palliatives will not be shared amongst politicians and their followers only,” the party said. 